;###################################################>
;################################################### INSTALLATION>
;###################################################>
;
@Node "2_Install_Man" "MANUAL!  Ooer indeedy missus! Fnaar fnaar!"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                  @{b}·M·A·N·U·A·L· ·I·N·S·T·A·L·L·A·T·I·O·N·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  Well  it's  really easy, init?  Just drag the @{i}TrinityPlayer@{ui} directory to
  anywhere on your harddrive and it'll be copied across.  That's basically
  all there is to it.

An  LZX  archive  containing  loads  of  CD ID's is supplied in the main
@{i}Trinity  Player@{ui}  archive  for you (if you got @{i}TP@{ui} from my website, AmiNET
don't  allow LZX archives).  Just un-archive it to the "Discs" directory
and  if  you  insert  any  CD  that  has  an  ID  in  there,  then it'll
automatically be loaded into Trinity Player (registered version only).

  @{b}PLEASE  NOTE:@{ub}   The AmiNET version of @{i}Trinity Player@{ui} doesn't contain the
  Discs.lzx  archive  because  LZX  archives  are  not  allowed on AmiNET.
  There's  no  way  I'm  gonna archive the Discs archive with LhA, because
  it's so crap.   The  Discs.lzx  (contains 885 CD ID's - archive is 133k)
  archive is available from my website - see @{"Author" link "5_Author"} section.
@EndNode

;################################################### INSTALLTION / AUTOMATIC
@Node "2_Install_Auto" "AUTOMATIC! Er... well. Can't think out `owt funny here."
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

               @{b}·A·U·T·O·M·A·T·I·C· ·I·N·S·T·A·L·L·A·T·I·O·N·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  You  can  use  the  @{i}Trinity  Player@{ui}  installer  to  install  @{i}TP@{ui}  to your
  harddrive.  Just follow these 2 very easy steps:

  @{b}1)@{ub} Double-click on the TP_Install icon.
  @{b}2)@{ub} Follow the on-screen prompts.

  It's so easy, it should be banned!

  The  TP_Installer  was  coded  by  me  in Blitz Basic 2 (like @{i}TP@{ui}), which
  obviously  means that it doesn't use @{i}Commodore@{ui}'s Installer utility.  The
  reason  why  I  coded  it  myself  was because I don't know how to write
  Installer scripts yet.
@EndNode

;################################################### EXTERNAL GFX FILES
@Node "2_Install_GFX" "GFX!  Nah... not here either."
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

        @{b}·I·N·S·T·A·L·L·I·N·G· ·E·X·T·E·R·N·A·L· ·G·F·X· ·F·I·L·E·S·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

 @{b}@{u}First, some info@{uu}:@{ub}
  If you don't like the look of @{i}TP@{ui}'s GUI gfx, you can change them yourself
  (you'll have to register to create your own), or you can use any GUI GFX
  files you can find on AmiNET, my website or anywhere else.

  External  GUI  GFX  end  in  .gfx  and can be located anywhere.  @{u}But@{uu} the
  default  GUI gfx that came with the @{i}TP@{ui} archive @{u}must@{uu} be called TP.gfx and
  @{u}must@{uu}  be  in  the same directory as @{i}TP@{ui}, or else @{i}TP@{ui} will quit out with an
  error message.

  Use  any  paint package that can load/save IFF files to edit the default
  TP_Gfx.iff GUI GFX that comes in the @{i}TP@{ui} archive, then run the TP Convert
  program  on  it  (registered  users  only)  to convert them to the right
  format,  crunch  it with StoneCracker and then run the converter program
  again.  You'll now be ready to use your new GUI GFX!

  The converted .gfx file is @{u}NOT@{uu} directly editable!  So please remember to
  keep the original .iff file!


 @{b}@{u}Installing GUI GFX@{uu}:@{ub}
  Very very easy!  Either set the @{"Tooltypes" link "3_Tooltypes"} to specify a file, or set the
  @{"preferences" link "3_PrefsWindow"} to specify a file.
@EndNode

