@Node "SONGED_TITLE" "Song Editor Window - Title"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} TITLE

    This is where you enter the title of the current CD.
@EndNode

@Node "SONGED_GROUP" "Song Editor Window - Group"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} GROUP

    Enter the group/band's name here.
@EndNode

@Node "SONGED_TRACKS" "Song Editor Window - Tracks"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} TRACKS

    Here you enter the name of each individual track one after another.
@EndNode

@Node "SONGED_TRACKNUMBER" "Song Editor Window - Track Number"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} TRACK NUMBER

    To the left of the @{"Track Name" link "SONGED_TRACKNAME"}, there is the track number.
@EndNode

@Node "SONGED_TRACKNAME" "Song Editor Window - Track Name"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} TRACK NAME

    This is the name of the track.
@EndNode

@Node "SONGED_TRACKNAME_EDIT" "Song Editor Window - Track Name Edit"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} Track Name Edit

    When  you click on a(n empty) @{"Track Name" link "SONGED_TRACKNAME"} name, it'll appear in the Track
    Edit  string.   Here  you  can  change  the  name  of the actual track -
    remember to press RETURN/ENTER when you've finished entering the name.
@EndNode

@Node "SONGED_TRACKNUMBER_EDIT" "Song Editor Window - Track Number Edit"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} Track Number Edit

    This is the number of the current track you're editing.
    See @{"Track Name Edit" link "SONGED_TRACKNAME_EDIT"}.
@EndNode

@Node "SONGED_PRINT" "Song Editor Window - Print"

  @{b}@{u}Song Editor@{uu} -@{ub} Print

  When  selected, you'll be asked if you want to send the current CD ID to
  the  printer,  or  to a file.  When sending to a file, it'll be saved as
  RAM:SongData.txt.
@EndNode

@Node "CloseGadget" "Close Window"

  @{b}@{u}Close Window@{uu}@{ub}

    This closes the window and returns you to @{i}Trinity Player@{ui}'s main window.
@EndNode

@Node "DepthGadget" "Depth Gadget"

  @{b}@{u}Depth Gadget@{uu}@{ub}

  Like  all  Workbench  windows  with  this,  this will shuffle the window
  between other open windows.  Hold down Shift then click the Depth gadget
  to directly send the window to the back (ie. behind all other windows).
@EndNode

@Node "DragBar" "Drag Bar"

  @{b}@{u}Drag Bar@{uu}@{ub}

    Just like all other windows, this lets you drag the window around.
@EndNode

;################################################### PREFERENCES WINDOW
@Node "3_PrefsWindow" "Usage / Preferences Window"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                          ·P·R·E·F·E·R·E·N·C·E·S·
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  The  Preferences window is currently under-going @{u}major@{uu} construction, and
  thus this section won't be done until it is complete.
@EndNode

;################################################### ABOUT WINDOW
@Node "3_AboutWindow" "Usage / About Window"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                         @{b}·A·B·O·U·T· ·W·i·N·D·O·W·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  The  old  About  window  has  become redundant due to the new layout and
  information  given,  so the old info has been removed from here.  As you
  can see, the new About window info hasn't been added yet.  So there.
@EndNode

@Node "ABOUT_REGISTERED_TO" "About - Registered to ..."
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                         @{b}·A·B·O·U·T· ·W·i·N·D·O·W·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  If  you  haven't registered @{i}Trinity Player@{ui}, then this will just say that
  it's registered to "@{i}no-one!@{ui}".

  If  you  have registered @{i}Trinity Player@{ui}, then your name and address will
  appear here.  Wowzers!
@EndNode


;################################################### KEYBOARD
@Node "3_Keyboard" "Usage / Keyboard"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                    @{b}·K·E·Y·B·O·A·R·D· ·C·O·N·T·R·O·L·S·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  You  can  control  quite a lot of @{i}Trinity Player@{ui} via the keyboard.  Here
  are the currently supported keys:

  pad = Numeric keypad


  @{b}@{u}WINDOW CONTROLS@{uu}@{ub}
    Left  cursor - Moves main window left.
    Right cursor - Moves main window right.
    Up    cursor - Moves main window up.
    Down  cursor - Moves main window down.

    1       - Move window to top-left of screen.
    2       - Move window to top-right of screen.
    3       - Move window to bottom-left of screen.
    4       - Move window to bottom-right of screen.
    5       - Move window to the centre of the screen.


  @{b}@{u}TRACK CONTROLS@{uu}@{ub}
    F1-F10  - This plays the cor(r)esponding track. Support for playing
              tracks 11-20 will hopefully be added soon.

    7/Home  - (pad) Play track 1.
    1/End   - (pad) Play last track.
    *       - (pad) Play track >20.

    0 (pad) - Stop playing.
    Enter   - (pad) Pause CD.

    4 (pad) - Rewind current track.
    5 (pad) - Fast forward current track.
    - (pad) - Skip back a track.
    + (pad) - Skip forward a track.


  @{b}@{u}OTHER CONTROLS@{uu}@{ub}
    F       - Toggle Shuffle mode.
    R       - Toggle Repeat mode.
    V       - Toggle Preview mode.
    G       - Toggle Program mode.
    E       - Eject CD.
    S       - Song Editor.
    P       - Program Editor.
    ?       - About requester.
    ESCape  - Quit Trinity Player.

    HELP    - This will bring up the TrinityPlayer.guide file if
              it's in the same directory as TrinityPlayer. Note,
              it's not context sensitive yet.
@EndNode
;################################################### COMMODITY
@Node "3_Commodity" "Usage / Commodity"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                            @{b}·C·O·M·M·O·D·I·T·Y·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  @{i}TP@{ui}  tries to install itself as a commodity.  Look at the @{"About window" link "3_AboutWindow"} to
  see if @{i}TP@{ui} could install itself as a commodity, or not.

  You  can  partly  control  @{i}TP@{ui}  with  the  Exchange  program  (comes with
  Workbench).  Here's how the buttons affect @{i}TP@{ui} :


  @{fg shine}TPs HOTKEY@{fg text}    : ctrl + lshift + t
                  This brings @{i}TP@{ui}'s window to the front of all
                  the windows on the current screen.

  @{fg shine}SHOW INTERFACE@{fg text}: This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into "Big GUI" mode.
  @{fg shine}HIDE INTERFACE@{fg text}: This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into "Small GUI" mode.
  @{fg shine}INACTVE/ACTIVE@{fg text}: This  doesn't  do  anything at the moment.
                  If  anyone  has  got  any  suggestions as
                  what these can do, then please contact me.
  @{fg shine}REMOVE@{fg text}        : This will make @{i}TP@{ui} quit. Basically.


  When I was designing @{i}TP@{ui}'s Preferences window, I forgot about making @{i}TP@{ui}'s
  hotkey  configurable.   Sorry.   I'll  implement  this into the GUI in a
  later  version.  Currently, you'll have to use the @{"CX_HotKey" link "3_Tooltypes"} tooltype to
  configure  it to how you want.  Also, if you've got any ideas for what I
  can use the Hotkey function for, then contact me.
@EndNode

;################################################### OTHERS
@Node "QSP" "Quick Selection Panel"

  @{b}@{u}QSP@{uu}@{ub}

  The  @{i}Quick  Selection Panel@{ui} is located to the right of @{i}TP@{ui}'s main window.
  It  is used as a quick shortcut to playing tracks, instead of repeatedly
  clicking on "Forward Track".

  The current playing track is shown as a de-pressed button on the QSP.
@EndNode

;################################################### TOOLTYPES
@Node "3_Tooltypes" "Usage / Tooltypes"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                            @{b}·T·O·O·L·T·Y·P·E·S·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  Due  to  a  problem  that  some  people were having with the Preferences
  Window locking-up when they clicked on "DEVICE", I've added Tooltypes so
  the user can configure @{i}TP@{ui} without having to use the Prefs window at all.

 @{b}*UPDATE*@{ub}  The above problem has been solved (see @{"History" link "4_History" 39}), but I thought
  I'd keep the above explanation in anyway.

  Currently,  there are some settings only available as Tooltypes, this is
  because  the  @{"Preferences  Window" link "3_PrefsWindow"} needs to be re-designed to accomodate
  them all.  And I'm sure I'll be adding more and more new settings, which
  would mean the prefs window would need to be re-designed every time - so
  the new settings are @{u}currently@{uu} only available in the Tooltypes.

  To  modify  the  Tooltype settings, click once on the @{i}TrinityPlayer@{ui} icon
  and then select Information from the Icon menu (Workbench) - here's what
  the Tooltypes do:

  @{b}@{u}TOOLTYPES@{uu}@{ub}
   @{fg shine}DEVICE SETTINGS:@{fg text}
    @{"SCSI_DEVICE       " link "PREFS_SCSI_DEVICE"} = squirrelscsi.device
    @{"SCSI_UNIT         " link "PREFS_SCSI_UNIT"} = 0
   @{fg shine}OTHER SETTINGS:@{fg text}
    @{"DISCS_PATH        " link "PREFS_DISCS_PATH"} = SYS:Utilities/TrinityPlayer/Discs/
    @{"OPEN_OWN_SCREEN   " link "PREFS_OPEN_OWN_SCREEN"} = 0
    @{"PUBLIC_SCREEN     " link "PREFS_PUBLIC_SCREEN"} = Workbench
    @{"CLOCK             " link "PREFS_CLOCK"} = 1
    @{"ASK_OVERWRITE     " link "PREFS_ASK_OVERWRITE"} = 1
    @{"BEEP_ON_ERROR     " link "PREFS_BEEP_ON_ERROR"} = 1
    @{"SHOW_TIPS         " link "PREFS_SHOW_TIPS} = 0
   @{fg shine}COMMODITY SETTINGS:@{fg text}
    @{"CX_HotKey         " link "PREFS_CX_HotKey"} = ctrl lshift t
   @{fg shine}GUI SETTINGS:@{fg text}
    @{"EXTERNAL_GFX      " link "PREFS_EXTERNAL_GFX"} = TP.gfx
    @{"WINDOW_BORDER     " link "PREFS_WINDOW_BORDER"} = 1
    @{"AUTO_ACTIVATE     " link "PREFS_AUTO_ACTIVATE"} = 1
    @{"POP_TO_FRONT      " link "PREFS_POP_TO_FRONT"} = 1
    @{"UPDATE_RATE       " link "PREFS_UPDATE_RATE"} = 46
    @{"PAUSE_FLASH       " link "PREFS_PAUSE_FLASH"} = 1
   @{fg shine}TRACK PREFS:@{fg text}
    @{"SKIP_BACK         " link "PREFS_SKIP_BACK"} = 10
    @{"SKIP_FORWARD      " link "PREFS_SKIP_FORWARD"} = 10
    @{"PLAY_INSERTED     " link "PREFS_PLAY_INSERTED"} = 1
    @{"PLAY_MODE         " link "PREFS_PLAY_MODE"} = 0
    @{"PREVIEW_DELAY     " link "PREFS_PREVIEW_DELAY"} = 5
    @{"START_FROM_TRACK  " link "PREFS_START_FROM_TRACK"} = 1
    @{"STOP_CD_ON_STARTUP" link "PREFS_STOP_CD_ON_STARTUP"} = 0
    @{"EJECT_CD_ON_EXIT  " link "PREFS_EJECT_CD_ON_EXIT"} = 0
@EndNode

;################################################### PREFS/TOOlTYPES HELP

-------------------------------- DEVICE SETTINGS
;
@Node "PREFS_SCSI_DEVICE" "Preferences/ToolTypes - SCSI_DEVICE"

  @{b}@{u}SCSI_DEVICE@{uu}@{ub}

  This is the device that @{i}TP@{ui} will use to access your CDROM drive with.  If
  you're  using  a Squirrel, then it'll be squirrelscsi.device.  If you're
  unsure  which  device  (found  in DEVS:) to use, then please consult the
  documentation that came with your CDROM software.

  Or you can have a look at the CDROM's mountfile (normally CD0:  which is
  in SYS:Devs/DOSDrivers) and see which device is mentioned.
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_SCSI_UNIT" "Preferences/ToolTypes - SCSI_UNIT"

  @{b}@{u}SCSI_UNIT@{uu}@{ub}

  This  is  the  SCSI  ID number of the CDROM drive.  I'm not sure what it
  would  be  on  an ATAPI CDROM - please check the documentation that came
  with the ATAPI software.
@EndNode

;------------------------------- OTHER SETTINGS
;
@Node "PREFS_DISCS_PATH" "Preferences/ToolTypes - DISCS_PATH"

  @{b}@{u}DISCS_PATH@{uu}@{ub} (registered version only)

  To  use  DiscID's  (a  file  containing  author/track  info about the CD
  currently in the CDROM drive), you need a place to load and save them.

  You  use DISCS PATH to specify the path to where you want DiscID's to be
  loaded  from  and saved to.  If using a directory, always add a slash to
  the end.

    ie.  SYS:Utilities/TrinityPlayer/Discs/
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_OPEN_OWN_SCREEN" "Preferences/ToolTypes - OPEN_OWN_SCREEN"

  @{b}@{u}OPEN_OWN_SCREEN@{uu}@{ub}

  If  you're  not  using  an  interlaced  screen  with  the MagicWB colour
  palette,  @{i}TP@{ui}  will  look crap.  So there's an option for @{i}TP@{ui} to open it's
  own 8-Colour interlaced screen.

   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that @{i}TP@{ui} will open
    it's own screen.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    OPEN_OWN_SCREEN=1     ;Own screen will be opened
    OPEN_OWN_SCREEN=0     ;Use the front-most screen (default)
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_PUBLIC_SCREEN" "Preferences/ToolTypes - PUBLIC_SCREEN"

  @{b}@{u}PUBLIC_SCREEN@{uu}@{ub} (not currently implemented)

  If  you  would like @{i}TP@{ui} to open on a screen other than the frontmost, you
  can specify which.  I think it may be case-sensitive, I'm not sure...
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_CLOCK" "Preferences/ToolTypes - CLOCK"

  @{b}@{u}CLOCK@{uu}@{ub}

  @{i}TP@{ui}  has  a  clock  near  the middle of it's main window.  You can either
  enable  it  or  disable it at your leisure.  As far as I've been able to
  tell, the clock uses no extra CPU time when enabled.


   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that the clock is enabled.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    CLOCK=1     ;Clock is ENABLED (default)
    CLOCK=0     ;Clock is DISABLED
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_ASK_OVERWRITE" "Preferences/ToolTypes - Ask Overwrite"

  @{b}@{u}ASK_OVERWRITE@{uu}@{ub} (registered version only)

  If there's an already existing DiscID file and you modify it in the Song
  Editor and this is enabled, you'll be asked if you want to overwrite it.
  If this is disabled, then @{i}TP@{ui} will just go ahead and overwrite it.

   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that Ask Overwrite is enabled.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    ASK_OVERWRITE=1         ;Enabled (default)
    ASK_OVERWRITE=0         ;Disabled
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_BEEP_ON_ERROR" "Preferences/ToolTypes - Beep On Error"

  @{b}@{u}BEEP_ON_ERROR@{uu}@{ub}

  Whenever an error of some kind occurs, @{i}TP@{ui} flashes the screen to get your
  attention.  If you're easily annoyed (you must be mad to be annoyed by a
  little screen flash), you can disable this.


   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that Beep is enabled.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    BEEP_ON_ERROR=1         ;Flash the screen when an error occurs.
    BEEP_ON_ERROR=0         ;Don't flash the screen when an error occurs.
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_SHOW_TIPS" "Preferences/ToolTypes - Show Tips"

  @{b}@{u}SHOW_TIPS@{uu}@{ub}

  When  you start @{i}TP@{ui}, you can have it bring up a "useful" tip on accessing
  a feature, how to do something - whatever.  Just run the ShowTip.exe for
  an example. Think an oh-so-important tip should be included? Tell me.


   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that startup tips will be shown.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    SHOW_TIPS=1         ;Show a useful tip upon TP start-up.
    SHOW_TIPS=0         ;Don't show a useful tip at all.     (default)
@EndNode


;------------------------------- COMMODITY SETTINGS
;
@Node "PREFS_CX_HotKey" "ToolTypes - CX_HotKey"

  @{b}@{u}CX_HotKey@{uu}@{ub}

  You  can  assign  any  key  combination  for @{i}TP@{ui}'s commodity hotkey.  The
  default is:  ctrl lshift t.

  Valid keys (as far as I know) are:

    ctrl
    lshift
    rshift
    lalt
    ralt
    lamiga
    ramiga
    A-Z

  eg. lshift lalt p
@EndNode

;------------------------------- GUI SETTiNGS
;
@Node "PREFS_EXTERNAL_GFX" "Preferences/Tooltypes - EXTERNAL_GFX"

  @{b}@{u}EXTERNAL_GFX@{uu}@{ub}

  This  specifies  which  external  gfx  file  TP should use for it's GUI.
  Please   refer  to  the   @{"Installing  External  GFX" link "2_Install_GFX"}  section  for  more
  information.
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_WINDOW_BORDER" "Preferences/Tooltypes - WINDOW_BORDER"

  @{b}@{u}WINDOW_BORDER@{uu}@{ub}

  You  have  the  option of making @{i}TP@{ui} open it's window with or without any
  borders. @{i}Command not fully implemented yet@{ui}.

    WINDOW_BORDER=1       ;Window border ON (default)
    WINDOW_BORDER=0       ;Window border OFF
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_AUTO_ACTIVATE" "Preferences/Tooltypes - AUTO_ACTIVATE"

  @{b}@{u}AUTO_ACTIVATE@{uu}@{ub}

  When  @{i}TP@{ui}  opens  it's  own window, you can have the window automatically
  activate itself.

    AUTO_ACTIVATE=1       ;Auto activate ENABLED. (default)
    AUTO_ACTIVATE=0       ;Auto activate DISABLED.
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_POP_TO_FRONT" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Pop To Front"

  @{b}@{u}POP_TO_FRONT@{uu}@{ub}

  When  @{i}Trinity Player@{ui} opens on a screen, normally if the screen is hidden
  from  view (behind another screen, for example), it stays hidden and you
  won't see @{i}TP@{ui} until you swap screens until you find the screen @{i}TP@{ui} is on.

  With  this  option enabled, you can have @{i}TP@{ui} move the screen to the front
  for you.

  POP_TO_FRONT  doesn't  take effect if @{i}TP@{ui} is set to open on the frontmost
  screen.

   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that Pop To Front is enabled.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    POP_TO_FRONT=1         ;Bring screen to front
    POP_TO_FRONT=0         ;Don't bother
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_UPDATE_RATE" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Update Rate"

  @{b}@{u}UPDATE_RATE@{uu}@{ub}

  When  I  started  @{i}Trinity Player@{ui}, the Track Time and Time Remaining time
  displays  were  updated every 50 vertical blanks (1 second on a 50Hz PAL
  screen),  when  @{i}TP@{ui}  was  ran  on an NTSC screen (or any other screen not
  running  at 50Hz, for that matter), the times got updated in less than a
  second.   This  is  due to different refresh rates (60 vertical blanks a
  second on an NTSC screen), so I decided to make it configurable.

  The  value  passed  is in vertical blanks (vblanks), so a value of 25 is
  half  a  second, 50 is one second, 100 is two seconds (2*50=100), 250 is
  five seconds (5*50=250), etc.


   @{u}Prefrences Window@{uu}:
    You  can  change the Update Rate by moving the slider.  Moving it left
    will decrease the rate, moving it right will increase it.

    Clicking on PAL underneath the slider will set the  Update  Rate for a
    PAL screen.  Clicking NTSC will do the same, but for an NTSC screen.

   @{u}Tooltype@{uu}:
    UPDATE_RATE=46         ;PAL  setting
    UPDATE_RATE=56         ;NTSC setting
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_PAUSE_FLASH" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Pause Flash"

  @{b}@{u}PAUSE_FLASH@{uu}@{ub}

  When  you  pause  a CD, you can have the Pause button flash or just stay
  lit.


   @{u}Tooltype@{uu}:
    PAUSE_FLASH=1          ;Flash Pause button upon pausing CD. (default)
    PAUSE_FLASH=0          ;Don't flash Pause button upon pausing CD.
@EndNode

;------------------------------- TRACK SETTINGS
;
@Node "PREFS_SKIP_BACK" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Skip Back"

  @{b}@{u}SKIP_BACK@{uu}@{ub}

@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_SKIP_FORWARD" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Skip Forward"

  @{b}@{u}SKIP_FORWARD@{uu}@{ub}

@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_PLAY_INSERTED" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Play Inserted"

  @{b}@{u}PLAY_INSERTED@{uu}@{ub}

  When  you  insert  a  CD, you can have @{i}TP@{ui} automatically play it straight
  away  if you want.  Useful if you haven't got your Amiga's monitor/telly
  turned on or something.


   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that Play Inserted is enabled.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    PLAY_INSERTED=1        ;Automatically play inserted CD.
    PLAY_INSERTED=0        ;Don't automatically play inserted CD (default).
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_PLAY_MODE" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Play Mode"

  @{b}@{u}PLAY_MODE@{uu}@{ub}

  There are currently 2 modes of play in Trinity Player:

   @{fg shine}End  Of  CD@{fg text}:  When a track starts playing, @{i}TP@{ui} will continue to play all
   following tracks until the end of the CD.

   @{fg shine}End  Of  Track@{fg text}:  When  a  track starts playing, only that track will be
   played.  So, when the end of it is reached, the @{i}TP@{ui} will stop the CD.


  @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
   Clicking on the cycle gadget will toggle between both modes.  The  mode
   visible will be the Play Mode.

  @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
   PLAY_MODE=1             ;Play until end of track.
   PLAY_MODE=0             ;Play until end of CD. (default)
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_PREVIEW_DELAY" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Preview Delay"

  @{b}@{u}PREVIEW_DELAY@{uu}@{ub}

  This  is  how  long  the  Preview  (sometimes called "Intro" in other CD
  players)  mode  will last for.  When previewing a track, you can specify
  the time (in seconds) each preview should last for.


  @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
   Click in  the  Preview  Delay box and enter how many seconds each track
   should be previewed for. Default is 5 seconds.

  @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
   PREVIEW_DELAY=5         ;Preview time per track is 5 seconds. (default)
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_START_FROM_TRACK" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Start From Track"

  @{b}@{u}START_FROM_TRACK@{uu}@{ub}

  If  @{"Play Inserted" link "PREFS_PLAY_INSERTED"} is enabled, you can tell @{i}TP@{ui} which track playing should
  start  from.   If @{"Play Inserted" link "PREFS_PLAY_INSERTED"} is disabled, then Start From Track takes
  no effect.


  @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
   Click in  the  Start From Track box and enter how which track number @{i}TP@{ui}
   should start playing a CD from if @{"Play Inserted" link "PREFS_PLAY_INSERTED"} is enabled.

  @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
   START_FROM_TRACK=1      ;Start playing from track #1.
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_STOP_CD_ON_STARTUP" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Stop CD on startup"

  @{b}@{u}STOP_CD_ON_STARTUP@{uu}@{ub}

  Everytime  you  start  @{i}Trinity  Player@{ui}, you can stop the CD in the drive
  playing by enabling this option.


   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that Stop CD On Startup is enabled.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    STOP_CD_ON_STARTUP=1        ;Stop CD when starting @{i}TP@{ui}.
    STOP_CD_ON_STARTUP=0        ;Don't stop CD when starting @{i}TP@{ui}. (default)
@EndNode

@Node "PREFS_EJECT_CD_ON_EXIT" "Preferences/Tooltypes - Eject CD on exit"

  @{b}@{u}EJECT_CD_ON_EXIT@{uu}@{ub}

  You  can  have  the option of @{i}Trinity Player@{ui} ejecting the CD out of your
  CDROM drive when you exit out of the program.

  @{b}Please Note:@{ub}  Your CD drive needs to have a motorised tray to be able to
  eject  CD's via software.  And as mine hasn't (it's a crappy MediaVision
  Reno  -  a flip-lid jobby), I don't know if CD Ejection works in @{i}Trinity@{ui}
  @{i}Player@{ui}.


   @{u}Preferences Window@{uu}:
    A tick (or "check mark") means that Eject CD On Exit is enabled.

   @{u}ToolType@{uu}:
    EJECT_CD_ON_EXIT=1    ;Eject CD when quitting out of @{i}TP@{ui}.
    EJECT_CD_ON_EXIT=0    ;Don't eject CD when quitting out of @{i}TP@{ui} (default).
@EndNode


;################################################### AREXX
@Node "3_ARexx" "Usage / ARexx"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                                @{b}·A·R·E·X·X·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  @{i}Trinity  Player@{ui} has an extensive range of ARexx commands which allows it
  to control other programs and be controlled by other programs. There are
  84 ARexx commands in this version.

  For example, you can use a program like Scala to start the current CD in
  the  CD  drive  playing when it gets to a certain effect.  By using @{i}TP@{ui}'s
  ARexx  port, you can write your own program (with any language that lets
  you use ARexx ports) that gets details such as the CD's track times, the
  CD's  title/artist/track  list/etc  or  whatever from @{i}Trinity Player@{ui} and
  then  insert  them into your program!  Thus creating a new interface for
  @{i}TP@{ui}  to  use!   For example, you can hide @{i}TP@{ui}'s GUI and use your new GUI -
  which  could  be small and compact and require a standard HiRes 4-colour
  screen!  Basically, you can do pretty much anything you want!

                               @{fg shine}@{bg fill}@{" AREXX COMMANDS " link "3_AREXX_MENU"}@{fg text}@{bg background}
@EndNode

@Node "3_AREXX_MENU" "AREXX COMMANDS MENU"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                            @{fg shine}·@{fg text}@{b}AREXX COMMANDS MENU@{ub}@{fg shine}·@{fg text}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

  All parameters with a @{fg fill}@{b}<@{fg text}@{ub} and @{fg fill}@{b}>@{ub}@{fg text} are required.
  All parameters with a @{fg fill}@{b}[@{fg text}@{ub} and @{fg fill}@{b}]@{ub}@{fg text} are optional.

    @{fg shine}@{b}@{u}INFORMATION@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
       @{"      CD      " link "AREXX_INFO_CD"}@{"    WINDOW    " link "AREXX_INFO_Window"}@{"    SCREEN    " link "AREXX_INFO_Screen"}@{"   PROGRAM    " link "AREXX_INFO_Program"}
       @{" PREFERENCES  " link "AREXX_INFO_Prefs"}@{"     MISC     " link "AREXX_INFO_Misc"}

    @{fg shine}@{b}@{u}CONTROLLING@{fg text}@{ub}@{uu}
       @{"      CD      " link "AREXX_CONT_CD"}@{"    WINDOW    " link "AREXX_CONT_Window"}@{"  REQUESTERS  " link "AREXX_CONT_Requesters"}
@EndNode

;--------------------------------------------------- AREXX COMMANDS

@Node "AREXX_INFO_CD" "ARexx / Information / CD"

                               @{b}@{u}CD INFORMATION@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}CD_TITLE@{ub}
    This returns the CD's title.
     eg. @{fg shine}The Best Of Belinda Carlisle #1@{fg text}

  @{b}CD_ARTIST@{ub}
    This returns the artist/band of the CD.
     eg. @{fg shine}Belinda Carlisle@{fg text}

  @{b}TRACK@{ub}
    This returns the current Track (either being played, paused
    or whatever). This still returns the Track number even if
    the CD is stopped.
     eg. @{fg shine}6@{fg text}

  @{b}SONG_NAME@{ub}
    This returns the title of the current track.
     eg. @{fg shine}Summer Rain@{fg text}

  @{b}TRACK_TIME@{ub}
    This will return the track's elapsed time.
     eg. @{fg shine}01:34@{fg text}  (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} a 5 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}TRACK_REMAINING@{ub}
    This will return the time remaining in the current track.
    NOTE: Everytime you call this, the Track's remaining time will
          be re-calculated.
     eg. @{fg shine}02:09@{fg text}  (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} a 5 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}DISC_TIME@{ub}
    This will return the total combined track times of the
    entire CD.
     eg. @{fg shine}62:28@{fg text}  (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} a 5 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}INFO_CD_PLAYING@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   CD is in Play mode.
        0   =   CD is not playing (not in Play mode).

  @{b}INFO_PAUSE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   CD is in Pause mode.
        0   =   CD is not paused (not in Pause mode).

  @{b}INFO_CD_OKAY@{ub}
    Sorry, but I'm not sure what this is supposed to return
    (haha! I NEVER plan my projects! Hahaha). Generally, if
    CD_OKAY=0, then don't try playing a CD, coz there might
    not be a CD in the drive,  or  the CD drive couldn't be
    intialised (SCSI Unit/Device is wrong/etc) or something.
    Returns:
        1   =   The CD drive is ready to play a CD.
        0   =   There's something wrong (no CD in drive/etc)

  @{b}INFO_SHUFFLE_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Shuffle Mode is enabled  (the Shuffle light is on).
        0   =   Shuffle Mode is disabled (the Shuffle light is off).

  @{b}INFO_REPEAT_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Repeat Mode is enabled  (the Repeat light is on).
        0   =   Repeat Mode is disabled (the Repeat light is off).

  @{b}INFO_PREVIEW_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Preview Mode is enabled  (the Preview light is on).
        0   =   Preview Mode is disabled (the Preview light is off).

  @{b}INFO_PROGRAM_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Program Mode is enabled  (the Program light is on).
        0   =   Program Mode is disabled (the Program light is off).
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Window" "ARexx / Information / Window"

                                @{b}@{u}WINDOW INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}WINDOW_TYPE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   The window is currently in SmallGUI mode.
        0   =   The window is currently in BigGUI mode.

  @{b}WINDOW_X@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate window position.
     eg. @{fg shine}118@{fg text}

  @{b}WINDOW_Y@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate window position
     eg. @{fg shine}64@{fg text}

  @{b}WINDOW_ADDRESS@{ub}
    This returns the main window's address in memory.
    The return value is in decimal.

  @{b}SMALLGUI_X@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate of the Small GUI
    (or last position if currently in BigGUI mode).

  @{b}SMALLGUI_Y@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate of the Small GUI
    (or last position if currently in BigGUI mode).

  @{b}SONGED_X@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate of the Song
    Editor's window.

  @{b}SONGED_Y@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate of the Song
    Editor's window.

  @{b}PREFS_WINX@{ub}
    This returns the X co-ordinate of the prefs window.

  @{b}PREFS_WINY@{ub}
    This returns the Y co-ordinate of the prefs window.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Screen" "ARexx / Information / Screen"

                                @{b}@{u}SCREEN INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}SCREEN_FONT_NAME@{ub}
    This returns the current screen's font name.
     eg. @{fg shine}personal.font@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_FONT_SIZE@{ub}
    This will return the Y size of the screen's
    current font.
     eg. @{fg shine}8@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_TITLE@{ub}
    This will return the title of current screen.
     eg. @{fg shine}Trinity Player V0.75@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_DEFAULTTITLE@{ub}
    This returns the default title of the current screen.
     eg. @{fg shine}Workbench@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_ADDRESS@{ub}
    This will return the current  screen's  structure
    address in memory. The return value is in decimal.

  @{b}SCREEN_WIDTH@{ub}
    This will return the current screen's width
    in pixels.
     eg. @{fg shine}640@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_HEIGHT@{ub}
    This will return the current screen's height
    in pixels.
     eg. @{fg shine}512@{fg text}

  @{b}SCREEN_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        0   =   The current screen is PAL.
       -1   =   The current screen is NTSC (yuk!).

  @{b}SCREEN_FLAGS@{ub}
    This will return the screen's current flag settings.
    I dunno what format the settings are off the top of
    my head.  I suppose you better look at some include
    files or something. Don't know really.

  @{b}SCREEN_BARHEIGHT@{ub}
    This returns the height of the title bar of the
    current screen (normally 11 with an 8-point font).

  @{b}SCREEN_MouseX@{ub}
    This returns the X position of the mouse.

  @{b}SCREEN_MouseY@{ub}
    This returns the Y position of the mouse.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Program" "ARexx / Information / Program"

                                @{b}@{u}PROGRAM INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}COMMODITY@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   @{i}TP@{ui} is running as a commodity.
        0   =   @{i}TP@{ui} failed to install itself as a commodity.

  @{b}AREXX_PORTNAME@{ub}
    This returns the name of @{i}TP@{ui}'s ARexx port. Useless,
    but who cares?
     eg. @{fg shine}TP.1@{fg text}

  @{b}AREXX_PORT@{ub}
    Again, this is useless, but ...
    Returns:
       -1   =   @{i}TP@{ui} was able to install it's ARexx port.
        0   =   @{i}TP@{ui} was unable to install it's ARexx port.

  @{b}VERSION@{ub}
    This returns the version of @{i}Trinity Player@{ui}  that
    is currently running, as a string. If there is a
    U character at the end of the string,  then that
    means that an  Unregistered  version  of  @{i}TP@{ui}  is
    running.  An R character means that a Registered
    version of @{i}TP@{ui} is running.
     eg. @{fg shine}0.75R@{fg text}
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Misc" "ARexx / Information / Miscellaneous"

                             @{b}@{u}MISCELLANEOUS INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}TIME@{ub}
    This returns the system's current time in 24 hour format.
     eg. @{fg shine}11:42:39@{fg text} (@{i}@{u}always@{uu} an 8 digit string@{ui})

  @{b}QUIT@{ub}
    Obviously,  this  will  make  @{i}TP@{ui} quit.  A value of 1 is always returned.
    Due to future expansion, assume a value of 1 for a successful quit, and a
    value of 0 for @{i}TP@{ui} not being able to quit yet.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_INFO_Prefs" "ARexx / Information / Preferences"

                              @{b}@{u}PREFERENCES INFO@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}SCSI_DEVICE@{ub}
    This will return the device entered in the SCSI
    DEVICE string in the prefs.
     eg. @{fg shine}squirrelscsi.device@{fg text}

  @{b}SCSI_UNIT@{ub}
    This will return the unit number of the SCSI
    device.
     eg. @{fg shine}1@{fg text}

  @{b}CX_HOTKEY@{ub}
    This returns the current Commodity hotkey setting.
     eg. @{fg shine}ctrl lshift t@{fg text}

  @{b}PLAY_INSERTED@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Play Inserted is enabled.
        0   =   Play Inserted is disabled.

  @{b}UPDATE_RATE@{ub}
    This returns the Update Rate set in the preferences.

  @{b}UPDATE_POS@{ub}
    This returns the value the Update Rate counter is currently
    at.  This  value increases by 1 every vertical blank and is
    reset when it gets to the Update Rate.

  @{b}CLOCK@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   The clock is enabled.
        0   =   The clock is disabled.

  @{b}ASK_OVERWRITE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Ask Overwrite is enabled.
        0   =   Ask Overwrite is disabled.

  @{b}POP_TO_FRONT@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Pop To Front is enabled.
        0   =   Pop To Front is disabled.

  @{b}PLAY_MODE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   End Of Track mode selected.
        0   =   End Of CD    mode selected.

  @{b}DISCS_PATH@{ub}
    This returns a string containing the path of where
    the CD ID files will be saved.
     eg. @{fg shine}DH1:Utilitites/TrinityPlayer/Discs/@{fg text}

  @{b}PUBLIC_SCREEN@{ub}
    This returns a string of where @{i}TP@{ui} should open it's
    window (if enabled).
     eg. @{fg shine}Workbench@{fg text}

  @{b}OPEN_OWN_SCREEN@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Open own screen.
        0   =   Use frontmost screen.

  @{b}AUTO_ACTIVATE@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Auto Activate window on.
        0   =   Auto Activate window off.

  @{b}WINDOW_BORDER@{ub}
    Returns:
        1   =   Window border on.
        0   =   Window border off.

  @{b}START_FROM_TRACK@{ub}
    This returns the Track number that's in the preferences
    regarding the first track that should be played if this
    mode is enabled.

  @{b}PREVIEW_DELAY@{ub}
    This returns the Preview Delay value in seconds.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_CONT_CD" "ARexx / Control / CD"

                                 @{b}CONTROL CD@{ub}

  @{b}STOP@{ub}
    This will stop playing the current CD.

  @{b}PLAYTRACK@{ub} @{fg shine}[Track]@{fg text}
    This will play the specified Track.  Remember,  check
    to see if everything is okay first (@{"CD INFO" link "AREXX_INFO_CD"}).
    The way the track will be played (until end of  track
    or CD) depends on the @{"Play Mode" link "AREXX_INFO_Prefs" 45} set in the prefs.
    A  return  value of 1 means that the track started to
    play okay. A value of 0 means that an error occurred.
    If you do try to play a track when something is wrong
    (no CD in drive/etc),  then  you'll  just  get 0 as a
    result - @{i}TP@{ui} will not crash (`be stupid if it did).

    If no parameters are passed,  the first track will be
    played.

  @{b}PAUSE@{ub}
    This will pause the CD  if  it's  playing.  A  return
    value of 1 means that the CD is paused,  a value of 0
    means that the CD is not paused (playing/stopped).
    To unpause,  just  call  this  command again and note
    the return result.

  @{b}REWIND@{ub} @{fg shine}<Seconds>@{fg text}
    This is the number of seconds the  currently  playing
    track should be rewound. Return of 1

  @{b}FORWARD@{ub} @{fg shine}<Seconds>@{fg text}
    This is the opposite of REWIND,  as it  goes  forward
    the specified numbers of <Seconds>. No return result.

  @{b}SKIP_BACK@{ub}
    This plays the previous track.  A  value  of  0 means
    that the previous track couldn't be played.  A  value
    of 1 means everything's fine.

  @{b}EJECT@{ub}
    This will try to eject the CD in the drive.  A  value
    is returned.  Not sure what it is, as I haven't tried
    to find out!  :)

  @{b}CLOSE_CDDA@{ub}
    This will free  all  memory  and  related  structures
    required for operating the CD drive.  @{u}@{b}DO  NOT@{uu}@{ub} use any
    of the above commands after you've used this command.
    If you do try one of the above commands  after  using
    the CLOSE_CDDA command,  you'll  hang  the  computer.
    A value is returned - like above - I'm not sure what.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_CONT_Window" "ARexx / Control / Window"

                               @{b}CONTROL WINDOW@{ub}

  @{b}WINDOW_BIG@{ub}
    This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into BigGUI mode.

  @{b}WINDOW_SMALL@{ub}
    This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into SmallGUI mode.

  @{b}WINDOW_TINY@{ub}
    This will put @{i}TP@{ui} into TinyGUI mode.

  @{b}WINDOW_TO_FRONT@{ub}
    This will bring the TP window to  the  front  if   it  is
    behind any others.

  @{b}WINDOW_TITLE@{ub} @{fg shine}<Window Title$> <Screen Title$>@{fg text}
    This lets you change the window/screen title(s).
    Say for example, you just want to change the Screen
    Title, you must put -1 as the Window Title. This stops
    the Window Title being changed. This also works the
    other way round.
    @{u}NOTE@{uu}: If you use this command while @{i}TP@{ui} is in SmallGUI
          mode,  then  it'll  be  changed almost straight
          away. That's because the CD times/etc are being
          displayed in the screen's titlebar.  Unless  of
          course there's no CD playing.

  @{b}DEFAULT_WINDOW_TITLE@{ub}
    If you've changed the window/screen title(s) and you want
    to change them back,  then you can use this command which
    will revert the titles back to the default strings$.

  @{b}MOVE_WINDOW_REL@{ub} @{fg shine}<X delta> <Y delta>@{fg text}
    This will move @{i}TP@{ui}'s main window relative to it's current
    position.  For example, if the window's current position
    is 104 and you give a X value of -3,  then the  window's
    new X position will be 101. A value of 3 will change the
    new X position to 107. Simple really.

  @{b}MOVE_WINDOW_ABS@{ub} @{fg shine}<X> <Y>@{fg text}
    This will move @{i}TP@{ui}'s window to absolute co-ordinates.
    So,  if you pass X as 34 and Y as 63,  then  the  window
    will move to them exact co-ordinates.
    @{b}WARNING:@{ub} If you give wrong values, you can cause @{i}TP@{ui}
             to  quit  with  an  error,  or most likely
             cause a GURU. Not very nice, mista.
@EndNode

@Node "AREXX_CONT_Requesters" "ARexx / Control / Requesters"

                             @{b}CONTROL REQUESTERS@{ub}

  @{b}REQUESTER@{ub} @{fg shine}<Title$> <Bodytext$> <GadgetText$>@{fg text}
    This will bring up a (EasyRequest) requester that can
    be used to notify the user, or can be used for a multiple
    choice question or summat.

        @{fg shine}Title$@{fg text}      =   This is what should be in the title
                        bar of the requester.
        @{fg shine}BodyText$@{fg text}   =   This is what should be in the  main
                        body of the requester. You can have
                        more than one line,  by  putting  a
                        Carriage Return (ASCII Char 10)  at
                        the end of each line.
        @{fg shine}GadgetText$@{fg text} =   This  is  what  should  be  in  the
                        button(s).  If you want to give the
                        user more than 1 choice,  then  you
                        must use the | pipe  character  in-
                        between each choice.

        eg.  REQUESTER 'Title!' 'How old are you?' '15|18|21|25+'

    Result: The right-most button will always return a value of 0,
            and for every extra choice,  add  a  value of 1 to the
            next-up right button.  Shit, it's too hard to explain,
            here's an example:

   REQUESTER 'Title!' 'Where do you live?' 'UK|AUSTRAILA|NEW ZEALAND'
                                            |       |          |
                                     .------'     .-'          !
                                  Returns 1    Returns 2    Returns 0

  If  you  were to put 'UK|AUSTRIALIA|MY RECTUM|NEW ZEALAND', and the user
  clicked on "MY RECTUM", then the return result would be 3.  Because it's
  the 3rd one to the right.

      @{i}Don't blame me for the way this works, it's Commodores' "fault"!@{ui}


  @{b}GETTEXT@{ub} @{fg shine}<Title$> <Default> <Action>@{fg text}
    You can get a string/integer from the user by using this command.

        @{fg shine}Title$@{fg text}  =   This is what should be displayed to the user.
                    Only one line allowed - and don't make it too long!

        @{fg shine}Default@{fg text} =   If you're using the STRING action (see below), then
                    this  is  the string that will appear in the string
                    gadget.  If you're using the INTEGER  action,  then
                    this is the numerical value that'll appear  in  the
                    integer gadget.

        @{fg shine}Action@{fg text}  =   This determines the type of input you require  from
                    the user.  STRING will let alpha-numeric characters
                    and INTEGER will only allow numerical characters to
                    be entered.

    Result: The entered string/value will be returned. If the user
            doesn't enter anything, then nothing will be returned.
@EndNode

;################################################### TROUBLE SHOOTING
;
@Node "4_TroubleShooting" "Trouble Shooting"
  @{fg shine}@{u}                                                                        @{uu}@{fg text}

                     @{b}·7·R·0·U·8·L·E· ·5·h·0·0·T·1·N·6·@{ub}
  @{u}                                                                        @{uu}

 @{b}Q.@{ub}   I  can't  find a program to load in the TP.gfx file so I can change
  the gfx, how come?


 @{b}A.@{ub}    You  can't  directly  edit  .gfx  files,  that's why you get an IFF
  version  of it.  All .gfx files are in a custom format, which also saves
  a  lot  of  disk  space  (for  example, an IFF GUI GFX file is 51k and a
  custom  .gfx  file  is 9k - even though they contain pretty much exactly
  the same data).


 @{b}Q.@{ub} I  run  TP on a screen with more than 8 colours, but TP's GUI goes all
  a sick purple!  Er...  why?

  @{b}A.@{ub}  Well that would be because you're not running MagicWB properly.  You
  should  have  your palette as the MagicWB palette AS WELL AS running the
  supplied (with MagicWB) MagicColours program which should hopefully sort
  this little AmigaOS prob out.   Get  the  MagicWB  archive  from  AmiNET
  somewhere - sorry, I don't know the URL.

  To give your Workbench palette the MagicWB colours, select Open from the
  menu  in  the Palette prefs program and then select the TP_gfx.iff file.
  This  should  give  you the MagicWB colour palette - you may need to run
  MagicColours to properly sort it out.


  @{b}Q.@{ub} When I click on the Prefs button on TP's GUI to edit the preferences,
  a big blank window  (with  possibly a couple of string gadgets) appears.
  Then I click in the window - but it just crashes!  Do I need to register
  to get access to this?

  @{b}A.@{ub} If you had to register to get access to the Prefs - how would you set
  which  device  to  use?   And  which  unit ID?  So no, you don't need to
  register to use the preferences.

  The  reason  for  this  Prefs  problem  is  because  you haven't got the
  required font installed.  In the early @{i}TP@{ui} releases, I stupidly forgot to
  include  the required fonts in the @{i}TP@{ui} archive, but in later releases - I
  included  them!   Yay!   The  fonts  required  are:   Personal.font,
  GTBGadget.font and XEN.font.


                       @{i}Anyone got anymore questions?@{ui}
@EndNode

